Background

This dataset was taken from kaggle. Here is the background provided by kaggle about the dataset: This dataset represents the second edition of What We Watched: A Netflix Engagement Report, covering Netflix viewership from July to December 2023. It captures 99% of all viewing activity on the platform during this period. Since the first edition, Netflix has added runtime and views (calculated as total hours viewed divided by runtime) metrics, as well as separating films and series data. Source

Data

Dataset for our Analyse

datatable(netflix |>select(`Daily Watch Time (Hours)`, `Monthly Income ($)`))

My goal is to explore how daily watch time is influenced by monthly income.

Question: does monthly income impact the daily watch time of individuals?

Full Dataset

datatable(netflix)

Objective

As mentioned earlier, we aim to understand the average watch time based on monthly income using simple linear regression. If the slope of the regression is significantly different from 0, we can conclude that monthly income helps explain watch time.

Hypotheses

If a relationship exists, the equation should be structured as follows: \[ Y_i = \beta_0\text{ } + \text{ } \beta_1 X_i\text{ } +\text{ }\epsilon_i \text{ }, \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2) \]

\[ X_i : \text{ Monthly Income} \text{ , } Y_i : \text{ Watch Time} \text{ , } \beta_0 : \text{intercept} \text{ , } \beta_1: \text{slope} \]

We then have the following hypotheses: \[ H_0: \beta_1 = 0 \]

\[ H_a: \beta_1 \neq 0 \]

\[ \text{Level of Significance } \alpha = 0.05 \]

Visualization

ggplot(data = netflix, aes(x = `Monthly Income ($)`, y = `Daily Watch Time (Hours)`))+
  geom_point(color ='gray' )+
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~x, se = FALSE) +
  labs(
    title = "Relationship between Daily Watch Time and Montly Income ",
    subtitle = "The monthly income doesn't have any impact on the daily watch time"
  )+
  theme_bw()

The above chart tells that there is no relationship between the daily watch time and the monthly income since the the trend line ( blue line) is almost horizontal. But lets run a linear regression test.

Linear Regression test

netflix.lm <- lm(`Daily Watch Time (Hours)` ~ `Monthly Income ($)`, data = netflix)
summary(netflix.lm) |> pander()
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 3.504 0.0574 61.04 0
Monthly Income ($) 1.014e-06 9.463e-06 0.1072 0.9146
Fitting linear model: Daily Watch Time (Hours) ~ Monthly Income ($)
Observations Residual Std. Error \(R^2\) Adjusted \(R^2\)
3500 1.441 3.285e-06 -0.0002826

Interpretation

With the above test result, we got a p-value of 0.9146 which is pretty high and greater than the level of significance. we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis. This mean there is a possibility to have a null slope. We can then conclude there is not a significant relationship between the monthly Income and the Daily watch time.

Checking statistic testrequirements

To conduct the linear regression test, we have 5 requirements that need to be met. They are;

  1. Linear Relation: the true regression relation between Y and X is linear.

  2. Normal Errors: the error terms i are normally distributed with a mean of zero.

  3. Constant Variance: the variance 2 of the error terms is constant (the same) over all Xi values.

  4. Fixed X: the Xi values can be considered fixed and measured without error.

  5. Independent Errors: the error terms i are independent.

copy from the textbook

par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(netflix.lm, which=1:2)
plot(netflix.lm$residuals, main="Residuals vs Order", xlab="",
     ylab="Residuals")

Requirements #1 and #3 are met, as there is no discernible pattern in the Residuals vs.Fitted Values plot.

Requirement #4 is assumed to be met since the monthly incomes are fixed.

Requirement #2 is not met, as indicated by the Q-Q plot.

Requirement #5 is met because there is no visible pattern in the Residuals vs.Order plot.
